---
title: 06 codecs
---

Q: What should you state before coding a codec?
A: Unit mapping, bit order, length rule, canonical form, and malformed-input policy.

---

Q: UTF-8 byte lengths by codepoint threshold.
A: `<0x80`: 1; `<0x800`: 2; `<0x10000`: 3; `<=0x10ffff`: 4.

---

Q: Encode U+20AC in UTF-8.
A: `e2 82 ac`.

---

Q: UTF-8 for `0x7f`, `0x80`, and `0x800`.
A: `7f`, `c2 80`, `e0 a0 80`.

---

Q: Which UTF-8 lead bytes are invalid outright?
A: `c0`, `c1`, and `f5..ff`; lone continuation bytes are invalid too.

---

Q: Why reject UTF-8 surrogates?
A: `0xd800..0xdfff` are UTF-16 pairing machinery and are ill-formed in UTF-8.

---

Q: What is the one-expression UTF-8 continuation-byte test?
A: `(b & 0xc0) == 0x80`.

---

Q: Base64 unit mapping.
A: 3 input bytes become 4 sextets.

---

Q: Base64 encode `Man`.
A: `TWFu`.

---

Q: Base64 padding for 1 and 2 leftover bytes.
A: 1 leftover -> `==`; 2 leftovers -> `=`.

---

Q: Why is base64 length mod 4 equal to 1 invalid?
A: One sextet cannot produce any whole byte.

---

Q: Pair-RLE encode 300 `A` bytes.
A: `ff 41 2d 41`.

---

Q: Worst case expansion for pair RLE.
A: 2x, when every run has length 1.

---

Q: Delta-zigzag-uvarint pipeline.
A: value -> delta from previous -> zigzag signed delta -> uvarint bytes.

---

Q: Delta-zigzag-uvarint for `[1000, 1005, 1004, 1010]`.
A: `d0 0f 0a 01 0c`.

---

Q: Bytes needed to bitpack `n` values of `k` bits.
A: `ceil(n*k/8)`.

---

Q: LSB-first bitpack sanity check for `k = 8`.
A: Output bytes must equal the input values.

---

Q: Fletcher-16 state.
A: `s1 = (s1 + b) % 255`; `s2 = (s2 + s1) % 255`; result `(s2 << 8) | s1`.

---

Q: When do you use CRC versus MAC?
A: CRC for accidental corruption; MAC for adversarial modification.
